    <text>
        <body>
             <div type="edition" subtype="ogham" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="pgl-Ogam" resp="#POC"><!--update lang and resp here-->              
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1" style="text-direction:up"/><persName><name nymRef="#?">ᚄᚓᚅᚐ<unclear reason="damage">ᚊ</unclear></name> <w type="formula" lemma="maqqas">ᚋᚐ<unclear reason="damage">ᚊᚔ</unclear></w> 
                    <lb n="2" style="text-direction:down"/><w type="formula" lemma="muccoviias"><supplied reason="lost">ᚋᚒ</supplied><unclear reason="damage">ᚉ</unclear>ᚑ<supplied reason="lost">ᚔ</supplied></w> <name nymRef="#?"><unclear reason="lost">ᚓ</unclear>ᚅᚐ</name></persName>
                </ab> 
            </div>                    
            <div type="edition" subtype="transliteration" xml:lang="pgl-Ogam" xml:space="preserve" resp="#POC">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1" style="text-direction:up"/><persName><name nymRef="#?">SENA<unclear reason="damage">Q</unclear></name> <w type="formula" lemma="maqqas">MA<unclear reason="damage">QI</unclear></w> 
                    <lb n="2" style="text-direction:down"/><w type="formula" lemma="muccoviias"><supplied reason="lost">MU</supplied><unclear reason="damage">C</unclear>O<supplied reason="lost">I</supplied></w> <name nymRef="#?"><unclear reason="lost">E</unclear>NA</name></persName>
                </ab>
               <!-- <ab type="list"></ab>-->
            </div>
            <div type="apparatus">
                <listApp>
                <app n="1">   
                    <note>The first word is complete and reads SENAQ. The second word begins with the letters MAC (or Q), after which the tip of the stone is missing. The first letter after the missing portion appears to be a Q, though, as the first stroke is damaged, it might be a C. After this there is a partly damaged section, 0.35m long, which appears to have had vowel strokes only, some of which are clear. The final two letters are clearly NA. This reading was generally confirmed on inspection of the 3d data. There is damage to the last score in both Qs so that it cannot be certain that they are not Cs. After the break only 4 scores are visible giving a C, which would be expected before the O if this is the remains of MUCOI. Regarding the E of ENA, three of the four notches are visible on the 3d model.</note> 
                </app>
                </listApp>
            </div>
            <div type="translation">
                <p>'of Senach son of the descendant of Ena' </p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                 <p>The last gap in the inscription contains vowels only. The last word, no matter how reconstructed, would appear to be some form of the name Enna or Enda (Manning 1989, 9).</p>
            </div>
